Infection with _Bonamia exitiosa_, Australia
--------------------------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 7 Jan 2016 from Dr Mark Schipp, Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture, Canberra, Australia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification (Final report)
Date of start of the event: 18 Mar 2015
Date of confirmation of the event: 6 Jan 2016
Date event resolved: 30 Apr 2015
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: _Bonamia exitiosa_
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country.

New outbreaks (2)
Summary of outbreaks, Total outbreaks: 2
Outbreak 1: Port Phillip, Victoria
Date of start of the outbreak: 18 Mar 2015
Outbreak status: resolved 30 Apr 2015
Epidemiological unit: coastal area
Water type: salt water
Population type: farmed
Production system: semi-open
Affected animals:
Species / Morbidity / Mortality / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / 0 (scale 0 to 5 / 3 (scale 0 to 5) / - / - / - / 0 / 0
Affected population: Trial farming of hatchery reared _Ostrea angasi_ in Victoria.

Outbreak 2: Westernport Bay, Victoria
Date of start of the outbreak: 18 Mar 2015
Outbreak status: resolved 30 Apr 2015
Epidemiological unit: coastal area
Water type: salt water
Population type: farmed
Production system: semi-open
Affected animals:
Species / Morbidity / Mortality / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / 0 (scale 0 to 5 / 0 (scale 0 to 5) / - / - / - / 0 / 0
Affected population: Trial farming of hatchery reared _Ostrea angasi_ in Victoria.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments: Specimens of _Ostrea angasi_ were examined by histopathology following low level mortalities in trial farming of this oyster species. Histopathology indicated the presence of Bonamia parasites. Subsequent diagnostic tests to confirm Bonamia infection and identify the species are included: Bonamia genus-specific TaqMan qPCR (Corbeil et al. 2006a): positive. OIE Bonamia genus-specific conventional PCR (Cochennec et al. 2000): positive, sequence homology with _B. exitiosa_. _Bonamia ostreae_ PCR (Ramilo et al. 2013): negative. _Bonamia exitiosa_ PCR (Ramilio et al. 2013): positive, sequence homology with _B. exitiosa_. _Bonamia sp._ 18S SSU (571-641) PCR (Corbeil et al. 2006b): positive, sequence homology with _B. exitiosa_. _Haplosporidia sp._ PCR (Carnegie et al. 2014): positive, sequence homology with _B. exitiosa_. ISH Bonamia genus-specific method (Ramilo et al. 2014): positive. The test results from April 2015 did not satisfy the OIE definition of a confirmed case of _Bonamia exitiosa_. Further diagnostic tests were performed, and these took considerable time.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; no vaccination; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (National laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / in situ hybridization (ISH) / 6 Jan 2016 / Positive
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (National laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / nucleotide sequencing / 6 Jan 2016 / Positive
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (National laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 6 Jan 2016 / Positive
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (National laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / real-time PCR / 6 Jan 2016 / Positive
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (National laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 29 Apr 2015 / Positive
AgriBio Centre (Regional Reference Laboratory) / Flat oyster (_Ostrea angasi_) / histopathological examination / 9 Apr 2015 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

The location of the outbreak can be seen on the map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

