[For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods, please refer to the OIE Aquatic Manual 2015, Chapter 2.4.2 "Infection with _Bonamia exitiosa_" at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/aahm/current/2.4.02_B_EXIT.pdf from which the following commentary is quoted:

"_Bonamia exitiosa_ is a Haplosporidia protozoan parasite infecting haemocytes of several oyster species and inducing physiological disorders and eventually death of the animal."

"_Bonamia exitiosa_ is an intrahaemocytic protozoan, but it can be observed extracellularly. This intrahaemocytic protozoan quickly becomes systemic and can be found in different organs, especially in the connective tissues of gills and mantle. In _Ostrea angasi_, the parasite is epitheliotropic, and apparently very light infections may cause a massive focal haemocyte infiltration with necrotic foci. In _O. edulis_, the parasite is associated with heavy haemocytic infiltration and appears in the connective tissue of different organs, mostly within haemocytes but sometimes outside host cells. In _O. stentina_, haemocytosis was not observed in animals found to be infected with the parasite."

"Clinical signs include dead or gaping oysters, but these clinical signs are not pathognomonic for infection with _B. exitiosa_ and could be indicative of other infections." - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3926358,288.]
